{"title_page": "Enter the Fat Dragon (2020 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 film directed by Wong Jing}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Enter the Fat Dragon\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| film name      = {{Film name\n| traditional = \u80a5\u9f8d\u904e\u6c5f\n| simplified  =\n| pinyin      =\n| jyutping    =  \n| translation = }}\n| director       = Kenji Tanigaki<br />[[Wong Jing]]\n| producer       = [[Donnie Yen]]<br />Wong Jing <small>(also exec.)</small><br />Connie Wong\n| screenplay     = Wong Jing\n| based on       = \n| starring       = Donnie Yen<br />[[Teresa Mo]]<br />Wong Jing<br />[[Niki Chow]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| studio         = [[Polybona Films|Bona Film Group]]<br />Bullet Films<br />Mega-Vision Pictures (MVP)<br />Sun Entertainment Film Group\n| distributor    = Mega-Vision Pictures (MVP)\n| released       = 23 January 2020 (Hong Kong)\n| runtime        = \n| country        = China\n| language       = Cantonese<br />Japanese\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $38,561<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl817136129/weekend/ |title=Enter the Fat Dragon (2020) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=21 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023034828/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl817136129/weekend/|archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NUM\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.the-numbers.com/movie/Fei-Long-Guo-Jiang-(Hong-Kong) |title=Joker (2019) |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |access-date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109195928/https://m.the-numbers.com/movie/Fei-Long-Guo-Jiang-(Hong-Kong)|archive-date=9 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Enter the Fat Dragon''''' is a 2020 Hong Kong [[martial arts film]] written and directed by Kenji Tanigaki and [[Wong Jing]]. The film is a remake of the [[Enter the Fat Dragon|1978 film of the same name]], and stars [[Donnie Yen]], along with [[Teresa Mo]], [[Niki Chow]] and Wong Jing himself in supporting roles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cityonfire.com/wong-jing-and-donnie-yen-to-enter-the-fat-dragon/|title=Donnie Yen eat-kicks in the New \u2018Enter the Fat Dragon\u2019 Poster|date=18 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fareastfilms.com/?news_post_type=donnie-yen-star-remake-enter-fat-dragon|title=Donnie Yen to star in remake of 'Enter the Fat Dragon'|date=7 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA fit police officer becomes overweight after being posted to evidence room and also as a consequence of emotional issues. He is send to Japan on a mission with a promise of transfer. He fails his mission because of the unsupportive police force. He is forced to be a crimebuster in Japan using his martial arts prowess and with the aid of his Japanese translator.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Donnie Yen]] as Fallon Zhu (Zhu Fu Long), the protagonist and a [[overweight]] police officer at [[HKPD]]. He's Chloe's fianc\u00e9, with whom he has a turbulent relationship full of ups and downs, but who saves her when she gets into trouble with [[Yakuza]].\n*[[Teresa Mo]] as Charisma/Christina, a [[Hong Kong]] restaurant owner in [[Shinjuku, Tokyo]], [[Japan]] and the former lover of Thor. She fled [[Hong Kong]] to Japan due to gambling debt.\n*[[Wong Jing]] as Thor, a former inspector of [[HKPD]], and the former lover of Charisma.\n*[[Niki Chow]] as Chloe Song/Chloe Zhu, a famous actress and the fianc\u00e9e of Fallon Zhu, with whom she gives a break, due to ups and downs in the relationship. \n*[[Naoto Takenaka]] as Mr. Endo, the [[corrupt]] chief inspector of [[Tokyo Metropolitan Police Department]]. \n*[[Tetsu Watanabe]] as Grandfather, the [[Oyabun]] of Higazhino Group and boss of Shimakura. \n*[[Hiro Hayama]] as Yuji, an [[adult video]] director and police informant from [[Japan]] who is murdered by Shimakura, a [[Yakuza]] boss because of drug smuggling committed by the Higazhino Group (the Yakuza clan headed by Shimakura).\n*[[Louis Cheung]] as Commander Huang, Fallon Zhu's superior in [[HKPD]].\n*Chaney Lin (Liu Qin Nan) as Little Tiger, the [[delivery boy]] and employee at Charisma's restaurant in [[Shinjuku, Tokyo]]. \n*Joey Tee as Shimakura, a Yakuza boss, leader of Higazhino Group (a Yakuza family from [[Tokyo]]) and the main antagonist of the movie. He murdered Yuji (the Japanese informant) because of drug smuggling committed by the Higazhino Group.\n*[[Wong Cho-lam]] as Traffic Cop\n*[[Lawrence Chou]] as Police Officer\n*[[Jerry Lamb]] as Police Officer\n*Masanori Mimoto as Benny, the [[Underboss]] of Shimakura at Higazhino Group.\n*[[Jim Chim]] as Bank Manager Zhan\n*Chan Friend as Robber\n*Bob Lam as Reporter \n*Tyson Chak as Reporter\n*Jessica Jann as Maggie, the English-speaking police officer and the bubble-headed interpretor to Mr. Endo.\n*[[Philip Ng]] as Jack, the main villain from 2005 film [[SPL: Sha Po Lang]] ([[Cameo appearance|Cameo]]). \n**'''Note''': Jack was originally played by [[Wu Jing (actor)|Wu Jing]] in [[SPL: Sha Po Lang|the 2005 film]]. \n*[[Anthony Chan (actor)|Anthony Chan]] as Chief Commissioner, the boss of Fallon Zhu and Commander Huang.\n*Kentaro Shimazu as Goofy, the Underboss of Grandfather at Higazhino Group.\n\n==Production==\nSpeaking about the film, in an interview, lead actor [[Donnie Yen]] said that the film is not \"necessarily\" a remake, director [[Wong Jing]] also stating it just happens to share its title<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maactioncinema.com/archives/7960|title=DONNIE YEN To Star In The Remake Of ENTER THE FAT DRAGON Directed By KENJI TANIGAKI. UPDATE: Latest Poster|date=18 March 2018}}</ref>. Yen previously also played a fat character in a TV commercial in 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IALFUb88gTw|title=Donnie Yen - 2015 Funny Commercial - SinoMax and SuperHeroFilms|date=10 March 2015}}</ref>.\n\n==Release==\nMega-Vision Pictures co-produced and distributed the film in Hong Kong and other territories. The film was released on 23 January 2020 in Hong Kong and selected countries. It also planned to release in China online platforms on 1 February 2020.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|7335600|Enter the Fat Dragon}}\n\n{{Wong Jing}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:Cantonese-language films]]\n[[Category:Films postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Films set in Japan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Japan]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong films]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong film remakes]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong martial arts films]]\n[[Category:Yakuza films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 film directed by Wong Jing}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Enter the Fat Dragon\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| film name      = {{Film name\n| traditional = \u80a5\u9f8d\u904e\u6c5f\n| simplified  =\n| pinyin      =\n| jyutping    =  \n| translation = }}\n| director       = Kenji Tanigaki<br />[[Wong Jing]]\n| producer       = [[Donnie Yen]]<br />Wong Jing <small>(also exec.)</small><br />Connie Wong\n| screenplay     = Wong Jing\n| based on       = \n| starring       = Donnie Yen<br />[[Teresa Mo]]<br />Wong Jing<br />[[Niki Chow]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| studio         = [[Polybona Films|Bona Film Group]]<br />Bullet Films<br />Mega-Vision Pictures (MVP)<br />Sun Entertainment Film Group\n| distributor    = Mega-Vision Pictures (MVP)\n| released       = 23 January 2020 (Hong Kong)\n| runtime        = \n| country        = China\n| language       = Cantonese<br />Japanese\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $38,561<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl817136129/weekend/ |title=Enter the Fat Dragon (2020) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=21 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023034828/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl817136129/weekend/|archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NUM\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.the-numbers.com/movie/Fei-Long-Guo-Jiang-(Hong-Kong) |title=Joker (2019) |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |access-date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109195928/https://m.the-numbers.com/movie/Fei-Long-Guo-Jiang-(Hong-Kong)|archive-date=9 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Enter the Fat Dragon''''' is a 2020 Hong Kong [[martial arts film]] written and directed by Kenji Tanigaki and [[Wong Jing]]. The film is a remake of the [[Enter the Fat Dragon|1978 film of the same name]], and stars [[Donnie Yen]], along with [[Teresa Mo]], [[Niki Chow]] and Wong Jing himself in supporting roles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cityonfire.com/wong-jing-and-donnie-yen-to-enter-the-fat-dragon/|title=Donnie Yen eat-kicks in the New \u2018Enter the Fat Dragon\u2019 Poster|date=18 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fareastfilms.com/?news_post_type=donnie-yen-star-remake-enter-fat-dragon|title=Donnie Yen to star in remake of 'Enter the Fat Dragon'|date=7 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA fit police officer becomes overweight after being posted to evidence room and also as a consequence of emotional issues. He is send to Japan on a mission with a promise of transfer. He fails his mission because of the unsupportive police force. He is forced to be a crimebuster in Japan using his martial arts prowess and with the aid of his Japanese translator.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Donnie Yen]] as Fallon Zhu (Zhu Fu Long), the protagonist and a [[overweight]] police officer at [[HKPD]]. He's Chloe's fianc\u00e9, with whom he has a turbulent relationship full of ups and downs, but who saves her when she gets into trouble with [[Yakuza]].\n*[[Teresa Mo]] as Charisma/Christina, a [[Hong Kong]] restaurant owner in [[Shinjuku, Tokyo]], [[Japan]] and the former lover of Thor. She fled [[Hong Kong]] to Japan due to gambling debt.\n*[[Wong Jing]] as Thor, a former inspector of [[HKPD]], and the former lover of Charisma.\n*[[Niki Chow]] as Chloe Song/Chloe Zhu, a famous actress and the fianc\u00e9e of Fallon Zhu, with whom she gives a break, due to ups and downs in the relationship. \n*[[Naoto Takenaka]] as Mr. Endo, the [[corrupt]] chief inspector of [[Tokyo Metropolitan Police Department]]. \n*[[Tetsu Watanabe]] as Grandfather, the [[Oyabun]] of Higazhino Group and boss of Shimakura. \n*[[Hiro Hayama]] as Yuji, a [[adult video]] director and police informant from [[Japan]] who is murdered by Shimakura, a [[Yakuza]] boss because of drug smuggling committed by the Higazhino Group (the Yakuza clan headed by Shimakura).\n*[[Louis Cheung]] as Commander Huang, Fallon Zhu's superior in [[HKPD]].\n*Chaney Lin (Liu Qin Nan) as Little Tiger, the [[delivery boy]] and employee at Charisma's restaurant in [[Shinjuku, Tokyo]]. \n*Joey Tee as Shimakura, a Yakuza boss, leader of Higazhino Group (a Yakuza family from [[Tokyo]]) and the main antagonist of the movie. He murdered Yuji (the Japanese informant) because of drug smuggling committed by the Higazhino Group.\n*[[Wong Cho-lam]] as Traffic Cop\n*[[Lawrence Chou]] as Police Officer\n*[[Jerry Lamb]] as Police Officer\n*Masanori Mimoto as Benny, the [[Underboss]] of Shimakura at Higazhino Group.\n*[[Jim Chim]] as Bank Manager Zhan\n*Chan Friend as Robber\n*Bob Lam as Reporter \n*Tyson Chak as Reporter\n*Jessica Jann as Maggie, the English-speaking police officer and the bubble-headed interpretor to Mr. Endo.\n*[[Philip Ng]] as Jack, the main villain from 2005 film [[SPL: Sha Po Lang]] ([[Cameo appearance|Cameo]]). \n**'''Note''': Jack was originally played by [[Wu Jing (actor)|Wu Jing]] in [[SPL: Sha Po Lang|the 2005 film]]. \n*[[Anthony Chan (actor)|Anthony Chan]] as Chief Commissioner, the boss of Fallon Zhu and Commander Huang.\n*Kentaro Shimazu as Goofy, the Underboss of Grandfather at Higazhino Group.\n\n==Production==\nSpeaking about the film, in an interview, lead actor [[Donnie Yen]] said that the film is not \"necessarily\" a remake, director [[Wong Jing]] also stating it just happens to share its title<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maactioncinema.com/archives/7960|title=DONNIE YEN To Star In The Remake Of ENTER THE FAT DRAGON Directed By KENJI TANIGAKI. UPDATE: Latest Poster|date=18 March 2018}}</ref>. Yen previously also played a fat character in a TV commercial in 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IALFUb88gTw|title=Donnie Yen - 2015 Funny Commercial - SinoMax and SuperHeroFilms|date=10 March 2015}}</ref>.\n\n==Release==\nMega-Vision Pictures co-produced and distributed the film in Hong Kong and other territories. The film was released on 23 January 2020 in Hong Kong and selected countries. It also planned to release in China online platforms on 1 February 2020.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|7335600|Enter the Fat Dragon}}\n\n{{Wong Jing}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:Cantonese-language films]]\n[[Category:Films postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Films set in Japan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Japan]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong films]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong film remakes]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong martial arts films]]\n[[Category:Yakuza films]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enter_the_Fat_Dragon_(2020_film)"}
{"title_page": "List of shipwrecks in August 1943", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe '''list of shipwrecks in August 1943''' includes [[ship]]s sunk, foundered, grounded, or otherwise lost during [[August 1943]].\n{{dynamic list}}\n{{Calendar ToC}}\n==1 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=1 August 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Bag\u00e9||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Brazil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: [[Convoy TJ 2]]: The [[cargo liner]] was ordered to leave the convoy because she was making excessive smoke. She was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Sergipe]] ({{coord|11|29|S|36|58|W}}) by {{GS|U-185||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 28 of the 134 people aboard.<ref name=Bage>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3031.html |title=Bag\u00e9 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Mangkalihat||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Netherlands}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy BC 2]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Indian Ocean]] ({{coord|25|06|S|34|14|E}}) by {{GS|U-198||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of eighteen of the 104 people aboard. Survivors were rescued by {{HMS|Freesia|K43|6}} ({{navy|UK}}). ''Mangkalihat'' was taken in tow, but foundered on 4 August at {{Coord|25|44|S|33|32|E}}.<ref name=Mangkalihat>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3032.html |title=Mangkalihat |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Mogamigawa Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The aircraft ferry was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] by {{USS|Pogy|SS-266|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194308/><ref name=Pogy>{{cite DANFS |title=Pogy |url= http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss266.txt |accessdate= 4 January 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Normandiet||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Denmark}}\n|desc=The cargo ship collided with {{SS|Maasburg||2}} ({{flag|Netherlands}}) in the [[Elbe]], She broke in two and sank. The wreck was dispersed in 1948.<ref name=Jordan446>{{cite book |title=The world's merchant fleets, 1939 |first=Roger |last=Jordan |publisher=Chatham publishing |location=London |year=1999 |page=446 |isbn=1 86176 023 X}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|PT-117}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Electric Launch Company|Elco]] 80' [[PT boat]] was beached and abandoned after being bombed by Japanese dive bombers in [[Rendova Island|Rendova Harbour]] ({{coord|08|24|S|157|19|E}}).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/10161.html |title=PT-117 of the US Navy |publisher=U Boat.net |accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|PT-164}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Electric Launch Company|Elco]] 80' [[PT boat]] was bombed and sunk by Japanese horizontal bombers in Rendova Harbor, [[Soloman Islands]] ({{coord|08|25|S|157|20|E}}).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/10208.html |title=PT-164 of the US Navy |publisher=U Boat.net |accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Soviet submarine|S-12||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Soviet S-class submarine|S-class]] [[submarine]] struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Baltic Sea]] north of Naissaay Island.<ref name=seekrieg194308/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/5097.html |title=S-12 of the Soviet Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-383||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Bay of Biscay]] west of [[Brest, France|Brest]], [[Finist\u00e8re]], France ({{coord|47|24|N|12|10|W}}) by a [[Short Sunderland]] aircraft of [[No. 228 Squadron RAF|228 Squadron]], [[Royal Air Force]] with the loss of all 52 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-454||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was depth charged and sunk in the Bay of Biscay north west of [[Cape Ortegal]], Spain ({{coord|45|36|N|10|32|W}}) by a Short Sunderland aircraft on [[No. 10 Squadron RAAF|10 Squadron]], [[Royal Australian Air Force]] with the loss of 32 of her 46 crew.<ref name=U454>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u454.htm |title=U-454 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==2 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=2 August 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Fortuna|1906|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[North Sea]] off [[Terschelling]], [[Friesland]], Netherlands by [[Royal Air Force]] aircraft. Six crew were killed.<ref name=seekrieg194308/><ref name=StrikeWing>{{cite book|last=Conyers Nesbit |first=Roy |title=The Strike Wings: Special Anti-Shipping Squadrons 1942-45 |publisher=Pen & Sword Books Ltd |year=2012 |page=69 |isbn=978-1781590287 |language=English}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese motor torpedo boat|No. 112||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=The TM 4-class motor torpedo boat was lost on this date.<ref name=\"Navypedia\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/japan/jap_aux_no102.htm |title=TM 4 class ex-Dutch motor torpedo boats of WWII, Japan |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese motor torpedo boat|No. 113||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=The TM 4-class motor torpedo boat was lost on this date.<ref name=\"Navypedia\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/japan/jap_aux_no102.htm |title=TM 4 class ex-Dutch motor torpedo boats of WWII, Japan |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|PT-109}}\n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Electric Launch Company|Elco]] 80' [[PT boat]] was rammed, cut in half, and sunk in Blackett Strait ({{coord|08|03|S|156|58|E}}) by the [[destroyer]] {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Amagiri|1930|2}} ({{navy|Empire of Japan}}). Two crewmen were killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/10153.html |title=PT-109 of the US Navy |publisher=U Boat.net |accessdate=2 August 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German lighter|Pierre||2}}  \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The lighter was sunk by a mine in the [[Black Sea]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soviet-empire.com/ussr/viewtopic.php?f=149&t=55255&sid=b64d81afc6dc3bf6ebf262ded5ddeaf9 |title=Soviet torpedo bomber victories during WWII |publisher=Sovietempire.com |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Romagna||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The tanker hit a mine and sank in the Mediterranean Sea off [[Cagliari]]. There were 14 dead and 11 survivors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.morgandiving.com/wrecks.php?id=5 |title=Romagna |publisher=www.morgandiving.com |accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Italian losses\">{{cite web |url=http://conlapelleappesaaunchiodo.blogspot.com/2014/02/cronologia-delle-perdite_14.html |title=Chronicle Italian Losses |publisher=conlapelleappesaaunchiodo.blogspot.com |accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-106|1940|2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|Type IXB submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] north west of [[Cape Ortegal]], Spain ({{coord|46|35|N|11|55|W}}) by [[Short Sunderland]] aircraft of [[No. 228 Squadron RAF|228 Squadron]], [[Royal Air Force]] and [[No. 461 Squadron RAAF|461 Squadron]], [[Royal Australian Air Force]] with the loss of 22 of her 58 crew. \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German trawler|V 420 Alcyon||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The naval trawler/''Vosportenboot'' was sunk off the [[Gironde]] estuary by [[Royal Air Force]] aircraft. Two crew were killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_conc_fpv.htm |title=Auxiliary patrols and minesweepers converted from fishing vessels in WWII, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=WarDiary4308>{{cite book|title=War Diary German Naval Staff Operations Division August 1943}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German trawler|V 1108 Arctur||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''Vorpostenboot'' was torpedoed and sunk in the North Sea off [[Texel]], [[North Holland]], Netherlands by [[Royal Air Force]] aircraft. 13 crew were killed.<ref name=seekrieg194308/><ref name=StrikeWing/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==3 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=3 August 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Italian submarine|Argento||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Kingdom of Italy}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The {{sclass-|Acciaio|submarine|1}} was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] ({{coord|36|52|N|12|08|E}}) by the [[destroyer]] {{USS|Buck|DD-420|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of four of her 49 crew. The survivors were taken aboard ''Buck'' as [[prisoners of war]].<ref name=Buck>{{cite DANFS |title=DD-420 |url= http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/destroy/dd420txt.htm |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Citt\u00e0 di Catania||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the Mediterranean Sea by the [[submarine]] {{HMS|Unruffled|P46|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|City of Oran|1915|2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy CB 1]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Indian Ocean]] {{convert|100|nmi|km}} northeast of [[Memba Bay]], [[Portuguese East Africa]] ({{coord|13|45|S|41|16|E}}), by the submarine {{GS|U-196||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 86 crew were rescued by {{HMS|Masterful|W20|6}} ({{navy|UK}}), which scuttled the vessel.<ref name=CoO>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3033.html |title=City of Oran |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 430||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The Type C ''[[Marinefahrprahm]]'' was sunk on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_mfp.htm |title=MFP landing craft, Germany |website=Navypedia |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kaisho Maru|1920|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Troopship|transport ship]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] south of [[Borneo]] by the submarine {{USS|Finback|SS-230|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Soviet guard ship|Priliv DK-5||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: The guard ship was sunk off Cape Set-Novoloc by German aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/russia/ru_cm_ii_gs.htm |title=Auxiliary Guard Ships of WWII, Soviet Union |website=Navypedia |accessdate=4 September 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Tyee Scout''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=During a voyage to [[Cape Spencer (Alaska)|Cape Spencer]] in [[Southeast Alaska]], the 23-[[gross register ton]], {{convert|49.8|ft|m|adj=on}} [[fishing vessel]] was wrecked on the coast of the [[Territory of Alaska]] at [[latitude]] [[58th parallel north|58 00 20 North]].<ref name=alaskashipwreckst>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-t/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (T)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-335||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[North Sea]] northeast of the [[Faroe Islands]] ({{coord|62|48|N|0|12|W}}) by the submarine {{HMS|Saracen|P247|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) with the loss of 43 of her 44 crew.<ref name=U335>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u335.htm |title=U-335 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-572||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] northeast of [[Trinidad]] ({{coord|11|35|N|54|05|W}}) by a [[United States Navy]] [[Martin PBM Mariner]] [[flying boat]] with the loss of all 47 crew.<ref name=U572>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u572.htm |title=U-572 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-706||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was depth charged and sunk in the [[Bay of Biscay]] northwest of [[Cape Ortegal]], Spain ({{coord|46|15|N|10|25|W}}) by a [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] [[Handley Page Hampden]] aircraft of [[No. 415 Squadron RCAF|415 Squadron]] and a [[United States Navy]] [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator|Consolidated PB4Y-1 Liberator]] aircraft with the loss of 42 of her 46 crew.<ref name=U706>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/boats/u706.htm |title=U-706 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 August 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Arrow|H42|6}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[A- and B-class destroyer|A-class destroyer]] was set on fire and severely damaged by the explosion of {{SS|Fort La Montee||2}} ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) at Algiers. Although she was towed to [[Taranto]], [[Apulia]], Italy for repairs, she was subsequently declared a [[constructive total loss]] and was scrapped in 1949. 28 crew were killed and 8 more died of wounds in the next days.<ref name=RNCas4308>{{cite web |url=http://www.naval-history.net/xDKCas1943-08AUG.htm |title=Royal Navy casualties August 1943 |publisher=www.naval-history.net |accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Catania|1918|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was heavily damaged during an American air raid on Naples. She was scuttled by the Germans on 15 September.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Dalfram||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Indian Ocean]] east of [[Madagascar]] ({{Coord|20|53|S|56|43|E}}) by {{GS|U-181||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of three of her 43 crew.<ref name=Dalfram>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3034.html |title=Dalfram |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Fort La Montee||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=The ammunition cargo of the [[Fort ship]] caught fire, and she exploded and sank at [[Algiers]], [[French Algeria|Algeria]]. 17 crew and 5 armed gunners were killed, 2 crew and 1 armed gunner died of their wounds in the following days. There were also many casualties aboard HMS ''Arrow'' and in the port.<ref name=RNCas4308/><ref name=CWGC>{{cite web |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find/find-war-dead |title=CWGC |publisher=www.cwgc.org |accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Harrison Gray Otis||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Liberty ship]] was sunk at [[Gibraltar]] by an Italian [[limpet mine]]. She was scrapped in 1949.<ref name=LibH>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/LibShipsH.html |title=Liberty Ships - H |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kembu Maru|1942|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed in the [[Pacific Ocean]] by {{USS|Seadragon|SS-194|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194307>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wlb-stuttgart.de/seekrieg/43-07.htm |title=Seekrieg 1943, Juli |accessdate=30 June 2015 |last=Rohwer |first=J\u00fcrgen |authorlink=J\u00fcrgen Rohwer |author2=Gerhard H\u00fcmmelchen  |work=W\u00fcrttembergische Landesbibliothek Stuttgart |publisher= |language=German }}</ref> She was damaged, but survived the attack.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Lombardia|1920|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[passenger ship]] was sunk during an American air raid on [[Naples]].<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Sant' Agata||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was sunk during an American air raid on Naples.<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German ship|SAT-1 Ost||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The heavy gun carrier was sunk in the [[Baltic Sea]] by [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] aircraft or by a mine. 28 crew were lost.<ref name=seekrieg194308/><ref name=WarDiary4308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Stanridge||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The ship was sunk at Gibraltar by an Italian [[limpet mine]].<ref name=Thorshovdi/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MS|Thorsh\u00f8vdi|1937|2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The tanker was damaged at Gibraltar by an Italian limpet mine. She was declared a total loss on 9 April 1945.<ref name=Thorshovdi>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/thorshovdi.html |title=M/T Thorsh\u00f8vdi |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck lis