GS|U-468||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Banjul|Bathurst]], Gambia ({{coord|12|20|N|20|07|W}}) by a Consolidated B-24 Liberator aircraft of [[No. 200 Squadron RAF|200 Squadron]], [[Royal Air Force]] with the loss of 44 of her 51 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-525||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|Type IXC/40 submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d, torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|40|12|N|37|29|W}}) by [[Grumman TBF Avenger]] and [[Grumman F4F Wildcat]] aircraft based on {{USS|Card|CVE-11|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of all 54 crew.<ref name=Card/><ref name=U525>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u525.html |title=U-525 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=4 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-604||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was depth charged and damaged in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|4|30|S|21|20|W}}) by a [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator|PB4Y]] aircraft and a [[Lockheed Ventura|PV-1]] aircraft of the [[United States Navy]] with the loss of 14 of her 45 crew. She was consequently scuttled due to damage received ({{coord|05|00|S|20|00|W}}). Survivors rescued by {{GS|U-185||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}), and she passed on some to {{GS|U-172||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). Fourteen crewmen were killed when  ''U-185'' was sunk later and it is not clear if the total loss was 14 or 28 crewmen.<ref name=U604>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u604.htm |title=U-604 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=12 April 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==12 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=12 August 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Clan Macarthur||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Indian Ocean]] {{convert|350|nmi|km}} east of [[Farafangana]], [[Madagascar]] ({{coord|23|00|S|53|11|E}}) by {{GS|U-181||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 53 of the 130 people aboard. Survivors were rescued by {{ship|French aviso|Savorgnan de Brazza||2}} ({{navy|Free French}}).<ref name=CM>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3042.html |title=Clan Macarthur |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 435||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The Type C ''[[Marinefahrprahm]]'' was sunk on this date. Salvaged and put in Italian service as {{ship|Italian landing craft|MTC-1103||2}} ({{navy|Italy}}) in May 1950.<ref name=\"MFP landing craft, Germany\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_mfp.htm |title=MFP landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|I-O-60||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The ''Siebelgef\u00e4\u00df'' landing craft was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_siebelgefass.htm |title=SiebelgefaB type personnel landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship= {{HSwMS|Illern}} \n|flag={{navy|Sweden}}\n|desc=The submarine collided with {{MV|Birkaland||2}} ({{flag|Sweden}}) in the [[Kalmar Strait]], [[Baltic Sea]] and sank with the loss of one crew member.<ref name=Times130843>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Swedish Submarine Sunk |day_of_week=Friday |date=13 August 1943 |page_number=4 |issue=49623 |column=E }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Disasters of the Deep: A Comprehensive Survey of Submarine Accidents & Disasters |first=Edwyn |last=Gray |publisher=Pen and Sword |year=2006 |page=179 |isbn=0-85052-987-5}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==13 August==\n