ner was captured in the [[Black Sea]] by {{ship|Soviet submarine|ShCh-209||2}} ({{navy|Soviet Union}}) and was left to sink.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soviet-empire.com/ussr/viewtopic.php?f=149&t=53387&sid=87dc208d7f79c1ee0a86901ed1e2494b |title=Soviet submarines in the Black sea in WWII (rework-update 2019) |publisher=Sovietempire.com |accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kaisho Maru||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy No. 4821: The transport was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] {{convert|300|mi|km}} northwest of [[Chuuk State|Truk]] ({{Coord|10|13|N|147|20|E}}) by {{USS|Tullibee|SS-284|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Three crewmen killed.<ref name=Tullibee>{{cite DANFS |title=Tullibee |url= http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss284.txt |accessdate=4 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Kaisho_t.htm |title=Japanese Transports |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=22 August 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Nishiyama Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship (a.k.a. ''Seizan Maru'') was torpedoed and sunk in the Pacific Ocean ({{Coord|02|55|N|136|43|E}}) by {{USS|Swordfish|SS-193|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Three passengers and four crew were killed.<ref name=Swordfish>{{cite DANFS |title=Swordfish |url= http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss193.htm |accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==23 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=23 August 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Ataka Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[cargo liner]] was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off Hamamatsu, Japan  ({{Coord|34|36|N|138|50|E}})  by {{USS|Paddle|SS-263|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). One of her 32-man Italian crew was killed. Survivors were rescued by fishing boats.<ref name=Paddle>{{cite DANFS |title=Paddle |url= 