ooner was captured in the [[Black Sea]] by {{ship|Soviet submarine|ShCh-209||2}} ({{navy|Soviet Union}}) and was left to sink.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soviet-empire.com/ussr/viewtopic.php?f=149&t=53387&sid=87dc208d7f79c1ee0a86901ed1e2494b |title=Soviet submarines in the Black sea in WWII (rework-update 2019) |publisher=Sovietempire.com |accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==26 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=26 August 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Christian Michelsen||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: [[Convoy UGS 14]]: The [[Liberty ship]] was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] {{convert|30|nmi|km}} east of [[B\u00f4ne]], [[French Algeria|Algeria]] ({{coord|37|12|N|8|26|E}}) by {{GS|U-410||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 47 of her 50 crew. Survivors were rescued by one of the convoy's escorts.<ref name=CM2>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3088.html |title=Christian Michelsen |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|John Bell||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy UGS 14]]: The [[Liberty ship]] was torpedoed and sunk in the Mediterranean Sea off [[El Kaka|La Calle]], Algeria ({{coord|37|15|N|8|24|E}}) by {{GS|U-410||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of one of her 72 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMS|BYMS-23}} ({{navy|UK}}) and {{ship|HMSAS|Southern Maid|T23|6}} ({{navy|South Africa|1922}}).<ref name=JB>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3055.html |title=John Bell |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Richard Henderson||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy UGS 14]]: The [[Liberty ship]] was torpedoed and sunk in the Mediterranean Sea off [[Sardinia]], Italy ({{coord|37|15|N|8|24|E}}) by {{GS|U-410||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 70 crew we