cort ship|SG 14||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The escort ship was bombed and sunk in the Mediterranean Sea by Allied aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://german-navy.de/kriegsmarine/captured/escorts/sg14/index.html |title=SG14 |author=Michael Emmerich |date=25 June 2003 |work=German Naval History |publisher= |accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-639||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Kara Sea]] ({{coord|76|49|N|69|42|E}}) by {{ship|Soviet submarine|S-101||2}} ({{navy|Soviet Union}}) with the loss of all 47 crew.<ref name=U639>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u639.htm |title=U-639 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==29 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=29 August 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship= {{HDMS|Bellona|1919|6}} \n|flag={{navy|Denmark}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: [[Operation Safari]]: The {{sclass-|Rota|submarine}} was scuttled at [[Holmen Naval Base]] in [[Copenhagen]] to prevent capture by the Germans.<ref name=safari>{{cite web |url=http://www.milhist.dk/besattelsen/august29/safari_uk.htm |title=Operation Safari - August 29th 1943 |author=S\u00f8ren N\u00f8rby |editor=Gert Laursen |work=Danish Military History |accessdate=26 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113214657/http://www.milhist.dk/besattelsen/august29/safari_uk.htm |archivedate=13 January 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/denmark/dk_ss_rota.htm |title=Rota Submarines (1920-1922), Danish Royal Navy|publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[HDMS Dampb\u00e5d A|HDMS ''Dampb\u00e5d A'']] \n|flag={{navy|Denmark}}\n|desc=World War II: Operation Safari: The auxiliary was scuttled off [[T\u00e5singe]] to prevent capture by the Germans.<ref name=safari/