mbing in the [[Isefjord]].<ref name=safari/> Salvaged in October 1943 and put into German service as ''Nordland''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.milhist.dk/vaaben/vands/nordland/nordland.htm |title=To gange s\u00e6nket af egen bes\u00e6tning - Art.skibet Niels Juel |author=S\u00f8ren N\u00f8rby |editor=Gert Laursen |work=Danish Military History |accessdate=12 February 2012 |language=Danish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716102256/http://www.milhist.dk/vaaben/vands/nordland/nordland.htm |archivedate=16 July 2012 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HDMS|Nordkaperen|1918|6}} \n|flag={{navy|Denmark}}\n|desc=World War II: Operation Safari: The minesweeper, a former {{sclass-|Springeren|torpedo boat|2}}, was scuttled at Holmen Naval Base in Copenhagen to prevent capture by the Germans.<ref name=safari/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/denmark/dk_ss_springeren.htm |title=Springeren torpedo boats (1917-1920), Danish Royal Navy|publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HDMS|Peder Skram|1908|6}} \n|flag={{navy|Denmark}}\n|desc=[[File:Peder Skram sunken in Copenhagen 29 August 1943.jpg|thumb|''Peder Skram'']]\nWorld War II: Operation Safari: The coastal defence ship was scuttled at Holmen Naval Base in Copenhagen to prevent capture by the Germans.<ref name=safari/> Later salvaged by the Germans and returned to service as the ''Adler'' ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navalhistory.dk/english/theships/p/pederskram%281908%29.htm |title=Peder Skram (1908 \u2013 1943) |editor=Johnny E. Balsved |date=4 April 2005 |work=Naval History  \u2013  Royal Danish Navy |accessdate=12 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104232710/http://www.navalhistory.dk/english/TheShips/P/PederSkram(1908).htm |archive-date=2012-01-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HDMS|Ran}} \n|flag={{navy|Denmark}}\n|desc=World War II: Operation Safari: The {{sclass-|\u00c6ger|submarine|2}} was scuttled at Holmen Naval Base in Copenhagen to prevent capture by the Germans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/denmark/dk_ss_aegir.htm |title=\u00c6ger Submarines (1915-1917), Danish Royal Navy|publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HDMS|Rota|1918|6}} \n|flag={{navy|Denmark}}\n|desc=World War II: Operation Safari: The {{sclass-|Rota|submarine|2}} was scuttled at Holmen Naval Base in Copenhagen to prevent capture by the Germans.<ref name=safari/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/denmark/dk_ss_rota.htm |title=Rota Submarines (1920-1922), Danish Royal Navy|publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HDMS|S\u00e6len|1919|6}} \n|flag={{navy|Denmark}}\n|desc=[[File:S\u00e6len and Nordkaperen sunken by their own crews 29 August 1943.jpg|thumb|''S\u00e6len'' and ''Nordkaperen'']]\nWorld War II: Operation Safari: The minesweeper, a former {{sclass-|Springeren|torpedo boat|2}}, was scuttled at Holmen Naval Base in Copenhagen to prevent capture by the Germans.<ref name=safari/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/denmark/dk_ss_springeren.htm |title=Springeren torpedo boats (1917-1920), Danish Royal Navy|publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HDMS|Sixtus}} \n|flag={{navy|Denmark}}\n|desc=World War II: Operation Safari: The minelayer was scuttled at Holmen Naval Base in Copenhagen to prevent capture by the Germans.<ref name=safari/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HDMS|S\u00f8bj\u00f8rnen|1939|6}} \n|flag={{navy|Denmark}}\n|desc=[[File:S\u00f8bj\u00f8rnen sunken 0422 29 August 1943.jpg|thumb|''S\u00f8bj\u00f8rnen'']]World War II: Operation Safari: The {{sclass-|S\u00f8l\u00f8ven|minesweeper|2}} was scuttled at Holmen Naval Base in Copenhagen to prevent capture by the Germans. Salvaged by the Germans but not returned to 