y|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: Three motor boats was sunk in Kronstadt Channel by {{ship|Soviet minesweeper|No-605||2}} ({{navy|Soviet Union}}).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soviet-empire.com/ussr/viewtopic.php?f=149&t=53730&sid=988abb615bce883cfe7f5e68e54c72d7 |title=soviet Naval Battles-Baltic Sea during WW2 (Updated 2019) |publisher=RedFleet |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==31 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=31 August 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Columbo'' \n|flag=flag unknown\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The sailing vessel was sunk in the [[Aegean Sea]] by {{HMS|Torbay|N79|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Flegetone||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The tanker was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] by {{HMS|Unsparing|P55|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese ore carrier|Kokko Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[ore carrier]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Luzon Strait]] ({{coord|28|30|N|123|06|E}}) by {{USS|Seawolf|SS-197|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of twenty crewmen.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Kokko_t.htm |title=Japanese Ore Carriers |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=31 August 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|LCT-154}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass2-|LCT Mk 5|landing craft tank}} was lost in the [[Gulf of Tunis]] ({{coord|37|08|N|10|58|E}}).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/19155.html |title=LCT-154 of the US Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=31 August 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Soviet submarine|Shch-130||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=The {{sclass-|Shchuka|submarine}} collided with {{ship|Soviet submarine|Shch-128||2}} ({{navy|Soviet Union}}) an