}}) by [[Short Sunderland]] aircraft of [[No. 228 Squadron RAF|228 Squadron]], [[Royal Air Force]] and [[No. 461 Squadron RAAF|461 Squadron]], [[Royal Australian Air Force]] with the loss of 22 of her 58 crew. \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German trawler|V 420 Alcyon||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The naval trawler/''Vosportenboot'' was sunk off the [[Gironde]] estuary by [[Royal Air Force]] aircraft. Two crew were killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_conc_fpv.htm |title=Auxiliary patrols and minesweepers converted from fishing vessels in WWII, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=WarDiary4308>{{cite book|title=War Diary German Naval Staff Operations Division August 1943}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German trawler|V 1108 Arctur||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''Vorpostenboot'' was torpedoed and sunk in the North Sea off [[Texel]], [[North Holland]], Netherlands by [[Royal Air Force]] aircraft. 13 crew were killed.<ref name=seekrieg194308/><ref name=StrikeWing/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==3 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=3 August 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Italian submarine|Argento||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Kingdom of Italy}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The {{sclass-|Acciaio|submarine|1}} was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] ({{coord|36|52|N|12|08|E}}) by the [[destroyer]] {{USS|Buck|DD-420|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of four of her 49 crew. The survivors were taken aboard ''Buck'' as [[prisoners of war]].<ref name=Buck>{{cite DANFS |title=DD-420 |url= http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/destroy/dd420txt.htm |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Citt\u00e0 di Catania||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the Mediterranean Sea by the [[submarine]] {{HMS|Unruffled|P46|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|City of Oran|1915|2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy CB 1]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Indian Ocean]] {{convert|100|nmi|km}} northeast of [[Memba Bay]], [[Portuguese East Africa]] ({{coord|13|45|S|41|16|E}}), by the submarine {{GS|U-196||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 86 crew were rescued by {{HMS|Masterful|W20|6}} ({{navy|UK}}), which scuttled the vessel.<ref name=CoO>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3033.html |title=City of Oran |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 430||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The Type C ''[[Marinefahrprahm]]'' was sunk on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_mfp.htm |title=MFP landing craft, Germany |website=Navypedia |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kaisho Maru|1920|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Troopship|transport ship]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] south of [[Borneo]] by the submarine {{USS|Finback|SS-230|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Soviet guard ship|Priliv DK-5||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: The guard ship was sunk off Cape Set-Novoloc by German aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/russia/ru_cm_ii_gs.htm |title=Auxiliary Guard Ships of WWII, Soviet Union |website=Navypedia |accessdate=4 September 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Tyee Scout''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=During a voyage to [[Cape Spencer (Alaska)|Cape Spencer]] in [[Southeast Alaska]], the 23-[[gross register ton]], {{convert|49.8|ft|m|adj=on}} [[fishing vessel]] was wrecked on the coast of the [[Territory of Alaska]] at [[latitude]] [[58th parallel north|58 00 20 North]].<ref name=alaskashipwreckst>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-t/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (T)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-335||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[North Sea]] northeast of the [[Faroe Islands]] ({{coord|62|48|N|0|12|W}}) by the submarine {{HMS|Saracen|P247|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) with the loss of 43 of her 44 crew.<ref name=U335>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u335.htm |title=U-335 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-572||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] northeast of [[Trinidad]] ({{coord|11|35|N|54|05|W}}) by a [[United States Navy]] [[Martin PBM Mariner]] [[flying boat]] with the loss of all 47 crew.<ref name=U572>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u572.htm |title=U-572 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-706||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was depth charged and sunk in the [[Bay of Biscay]] northwest of [[Cape Ortegal]], Spain ({{coord|46|15|N|10|25|W}}) by a [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] [[Handley Page Hampden]] aircraft of [[No. 415 Squadron RCAF|415 Squadron]] and a [[United States Navy]] [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator|Consolidated PB4Y-1 Liberator]] aircraft with the loss of 42 of her 46 crew.<ref name=U706>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/boats/u706.htm |title=U-706 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 August 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Arrow|H42|6}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[A- and B-class destroyer|A-class destroyer]] was set on fire and severely damaged by the explosion of {{SS|Fort La Montee||2}} ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) at Algiers. Although she was towed to [[Taranto]], [[Apulia]], Italy for repairs, she was subsequently declared a [[constructive total loss]] and was scrapped in 1949. 28 crew were killed and 8 more died of wounds in the next days.<ref name=RNCas4308>{{cite web |url=http://www.naval-history.net/xDKCas1943-08AUG.htm |title=Royal Navy casualties August 1943 |publisher=www.naval-history.net |accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Catania|1918|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was heavily damaged during an American air raid on Naples. She was scuttled by the Germans on 15 September.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Dalfram||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Indian Ocean]] east of [[Madagascar]] ({{Coord|20|53|S|56|43|E}}) by {{GS|U-181||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of three of her 43 crew.<ref name=Dalfram>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3034.html |title=Dalfram |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Fort La Montee||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=The ammunition cargo of the [[Fort ship]] caught fire, and she exploded and sank at [[Algiers]], [[French Algeria|Algeria]]. 17 crew and 5 armed gunners were killed, 2 crew and 1 armed gunner died of their wounds in the following days. There were also many casualties aboard HMS ''Arrow'' and in the port.<ref name=RNCas4308/><ref name=CWGC>{{cite web |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find/find-war-dead |title=CWGC |publisher=www.cwgc.org |accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Harrison Gray Otis||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Liberty ship]] was sunk at [[Gibraltar]] by an Italian [[limpet mine]]. She was scrapped in 1949.<ref name=LibH>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/LibShipsH.html |title=Liberty Ships - H |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kembu Maru|1942|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed in the [[Pacific Ocean]] by {{USS|Seadragon|SS-194|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194307>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wlb-stuttgart.de/seekrieg/43-07.htm |title=Seekrieg 1943, Juli |accessdate=30 June 2015 |last=Rohwer |first=J\u00fcrgen |authorlink=J\u00fcrgen Rohwer |author2=Gerhard H\u00fcmmelchen  |work=W\u00fcrttembergische Landesbibliothek Stuttgart |publisher= |language=German }}</ref> She was damaged, but survived the attack.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Lombardia|1920|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[passenger ship]] was sunk during an American air raid on [[Naples]].<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Sant' Agata||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was sunk during an American air raid on Naples.<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German ship|SAT-1 Ost||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The heavy gun carrier was sunk in the [[Baltic Sea]] by [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] aircraft or by a mine. 28 crew were lost.<ref name=seekrieg194308/><ref name=WarDiary4308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Stanridge||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The ship was sunk at Gibraltar by an Italian [[limpet mine]].<ref name=Thorshovdi/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MS|Thorsh\u00f8vdi|1937|2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The tanker was damaged at Gibraltar by an Italian limpet mine. She was declared a total loss on 9 April 1945.<ref name=Thorshovdi>