rg/ships/germany/ger_amph_mfp.htm |title=MFP landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 440||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The Type C ''[[Marinefahrprahm]]'' was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"MFP landing craft, Germany\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_mfp.htm |title=MFP landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Fernhill|1926|2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] ({{coord|6|58|N|19|15|W}}) by {{GS|U-757||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of four of her 44 crew. One survivor was taken aboard ''U-757'' as a [[prisoner of war]]. The other survivors were rescued by {{MV|Idaho|1941|2}} ({{flag|United States|1912}}).<ref name=Fernhill>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/fernhill.html |title= M/S Fernhill |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=12 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=FernhillU757>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3039.html |title=Fernhill |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary Ellen''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=The 15-[[gross register ton]], {{convert|38.9|ft|m|1|adj=on}} [[fishing vessel]] was destroyed by fire at [[Icy Point]] in [[Southeast Alaska]].<ref name=alaskashipwrecksm>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-m/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (M)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Nantaise||2}} \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Aegean Sea]] by {{HMS|Rorqual|N74|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|PiLB 59||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The PiLB 39 Type personnel landing craft was lost on this date.<ref name=\"navypedia.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_pilb39.htm |title=PiLB 39 Type personnel landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German siebel ferry|SF 86||2}}    \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The [[Siebel ferry]] was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_sf40.htm |title=Siebelfahre 40 and Siebelfahre 41, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-84|1941|2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|27|55|N|68|03|W}}) by a [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator|Consolidated PB4Y Liberator]] aircraft of the [[United States Navy]] with the loss of all 46 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-117|1941|2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type X submarine|Type XB submarine]] was sunk in the [[North Atlantic]] by [[depth charge]]s and torpedoes dropped by a [[Grumman TBM Avenger]] aircraft from {{USS|Card|CVE-11|6}} ({{navy|USA}}). All 62 crew were killed.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-615||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was depth charged and sunk in the [[Caribbean Sea]] ({{coord|12|38|N|65|15|W}}) by six [[Martin PBM Mariner]] and a [[Lockheed Ventura]] aircraft of the [[United States Navy]] with the loss of four of her 47 crew.<ref name=U615>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u615.htm |title=U-615 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Umvuma||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Indian Ocean]] south east of [[Port Louis]], [[Mauri