ugust 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Fusijama||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War I]]I: The blockade breaker was bombed and sunk in the [[Bay of Biscay]] off [[Bordeaux]], [[Gironde]], France by [[Royal Air Force]] aircraft.<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Jsub|Ro-35||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Kaich\u016b type submarine|''Kaich\u016b VII'' type submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Coral Sea]] ({{coord|12|57|S|164|23|E|}}) by {{USS|Ellet|DD-398|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Lost with all 66 hands.<ref name=seekrieg194308/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/RO-35_t.htm |title=Imperial Submarines |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=25 August 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Shkval||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: The rescue tug struck a [[naval mine|mine]] laid by {{GS|U-625||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) and sank in the [[Yugor Strait]]. There were 47 dead and only 5 survivors.<ref name=seekrieg194307/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soviet-empire.com/ussr/viewtopic.php?f=149&t=51741 |title=U-Boats in Soviet Artic waters |publisher=www.soviet-empire.com |accessdate=13 February 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Siqueira Campos||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Brazil|1883}}\n|desc=The [[passenger ship]] collided with {{SS|Cuyab\u00e1||2}} ({{flag|Brazil|1883}}) off Caponga. She was beached but was declared a [[constructive total loss]].<ref name=Jordan445>{{cite book |title=The world's merchant fleets, 1939 |first=Roger |last=Jordan |publisher=Chatham publishing |location=London |year=1999 |page=445 |isbn=1 86176 023 X}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-523||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|Type IXC submarine]] was depth charged and sunk in the [[Bay of Biscay]] by {{HMS|Wanderer|D74|6}} and {{HMS|Wallflower|K44