 [[Liberty ship]] was torpedoed and sunk in the Mediterranean Sea off [[Sardinia]], Italy ({{coord|37|15|N|8|24|E}}) by {{GS|U-410||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 70 crew were rescued by {{ship|HMSAS|Southern Maid|T23|6}} ({{navy|South Africa|1922}}) or reached land in their [[lifeboat (shipboard)|lifeboats]].<ref name=LibR>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/LibShipsR.html |title=Liberty Ships - R |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=RH>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3054.html |title=Richard Henderson |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Soviet submarine|ShCh-203||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Shchuka|submarine}} was torpedoed and sunk in the Black Sea west of [[Yevpatoriya]], Crimea ({{coord|45|12|N|32|47|E}}) by {{ship|Italian submarine|SB 4||2}} ({{navy|Kingdom of Italy}}).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/5034.html |title=ShCh-203 of the Soviet Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|StuBo 1001||2}}    \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc= The StuBo42 type landing craft/motor launch was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_stubo42.htm |title=StuBo42 type personnel landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==27 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=27 August 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Citt\u00e0 di Spezia||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] by {{HMS|Unruffled|P46|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Egret|L75|6}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Egret|sloop|0}} [[Sloop-of-war|sloop]] was bombed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off the coast of Portugal ({{coord|42|10|N|9|22|W}}) by [[Dornier Do 217]] aircraft of the [[Luftwaffe]] carrying [[Henschel Hs 293]] [[glider bomb]]s. A total of 198 people were lost.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Havbris II'' \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The fishing vessel was captured by {{HMS|Untiring|P59|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) in the [[Norwegian Sea]] off [[God\u00f8]] and was scuttled. Her crew were taken as [[prisoners of war]].<ref name=seekrieg194308/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|John Bell||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Liberty ship]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] off [[Sardinia]], Italy ({{coord|37|15|N|8|24|E}}) by {{GS|U-410||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}).<ref name=LibJo>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/LibShipsJo.html |title=Liberty Ships - Joaquin - Johns |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|LCT-319}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=The {{sclass-|LCT-1|landing craft tank}} ran aground and sank in the harbor at [[Kiska, Alaska|Kiska]] in the [[Aleutian Islands]] during a storm.<ref name=alaskashipwrecksl>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-l/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (L)]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/19320.html |title=LCT-319 of the US Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Meizan Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo liner]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Tablas Strait]] north east of [[Mindoro]], Philippines ({{Coord|13|13|N|121|23|E}}) by {{USS|Grayling|SS-209|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Grayling>{{cite DANFS |title=Grayling |url= http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss209.txt |accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=VK>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/venkoh.html |title=D/S Ven Koh |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Soviet motor torpedo boat|No. 15||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=The G-5-class motor torpedo boat was lost on this date.<ref name=\"G-5 class motor torpedo boat, USSR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/russia/ru_cf_g5.htm |title=G-5 class motor torpedo boat, USSR |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Rastrello|1895|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Mediterranean Sea {{convert|48|nmi|km}} off [[Brindisi]] by {{HMS|Unruffled|P46|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194308/><ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=1140419|shipname=Rastrello |accessdate=5 December 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|StuBo 1091||2}}    \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The StuBo42 type landing craft/motor launch was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_stubo42.htm |title=StuBo42 type personnel landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Taifuku Maru||2}} \n|flag={{army|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy FU-806: The cargo liner was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off [[Kyushu]] ({{Coord|32|28|N|132|23|E}}) by {{USS|Pollack|SS-180|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). 14 troops and 14 crewmen killed. Survivors were rescued by {{ship|Japanese minesweeper|W-17||2}} ({{navy|Empire of Japan}}).<ref name=Pollack>{{cite DANFS |title=Pollack |url= http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss180.txt |accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Tokai Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Pacific Ocean so